ce:section.ce:para:
Green NMs catalyze the degradation of organic contaminants by photocatalysis to produce non-toxic byproducts or undergo complete mineralization (Yaqoob et al., 2020). Photocatalysis is the process by which a catalyst is activated or stimulated in the presence of sunlight, visible light, or UV light (Zhang et al., 2021a). Generally, two processes occur during photocatalysis, including (i) contaminant degradation and (ii) contaminant mineralization (Fig. 3
                           ). Organic pollutants split or decompose into several products during photocatalytic degradation and are completely degraded into H2O, CO2, and inorganic ions via mineralization. Several factors affect photocatalytic reactions, including the nature and concentration of the pollutants involved, the concentration of used photocatalysts, surface morphology, surface area, pH, temperature, and the intensity and duration of light irradiation (Zhu et al., 2021). Several actions can increase the photocatalytic activity of NMs, including: (i) variation of the surface area to volume ratio of the photocatalyst, (ii) combination of the photocatalyst with other metal and metal oxide NPs, and (iii) doping the photocatalyst to increase the number of electron-hole pairs present (Gokulakrishnan et al., 2021). Studies indicate that doping metal oxide photocatalysts with N, Cu, Zr, or Ce significantly improves their stability and photocatalytic performance (Anfar et al., 2021; Gao et al., 2021a). Photocatalysts generate active species during the degradation of water contaminants with a high oxidizing potential, which can effectively oxidize most organic pollutants in wastewater to harmless molecules. Photogenerated charge carriers produce electron-hole pairs during their transfer from the valence band to the conduction band. The photogenerated electron-hole pairs are then utilized for photo-oxidation and photo-reduction reactions through which the molecular chains of the organic pollutants undergo degradation. As a result, the photocatalytic capacity of any semiconducting metal oxide is associated with two aspects: (i) the creation of •OH by the oxidation of OH anions (photo-oxidation reaction), and (ii) the production of O2
                           •‒ via the reduction of O2 (photo-reduction reaction) (Anfar et al., 2021).

Membrane separation technology, which is based on the removal of contaminants by size exclusion, is also a key method used in water reclamation (Gao et al., 2021b). However, many hurdles prevent the further advancement of membrane technology, including the high energy demand, biofouling, and technical complexity. As a result, several advanced nanocomposite membranes that incorporate novel functionalized NPs have been developed. This new membrane class exhibits unique physiochemical properties, including mechanical and thermal stability, hydrophilicity, high porosity, increased permeability, antifouling and antimicrobial properties, and photocatalytic and adsorptive capacities (Zhang et al., 2021b) Monometallic FeNPs and bimetallic Fe/Pd NPs (20–30 nm) derived from green tea extracts and immobilized in a polymer film were employed in one study for the preparation of polyvinylidene difluoride membranes (Smuleac et al., 2011). Green tea extracts include a variety of polyphenols that can act as reducing, chelating, and capping agents, providing protection against the oxidation and aggregation of the prepared particles, thereby increasing their longevity. The membrane-supported NPs dechlorinated trichloroethylene, a highly toxic organic pollutant in groundwater, via a reductive degradation mechanism. The addition of Pd resulted in a two-fold increase in the surface normalized rate constant (k

                              SA
                           ) from 0.005 to 0.008 L/m2 h. Adsorption is currently the most widely used method for the removal of water pollutants as a result of its simplicity, high efficiency, low energy requirements, and lack of secondary pollutants (Mpatani et al., 2021). Conventional adsorbents frequently have several drawbacks such as low capacity, reduced selectivity, and short adsorption–reuse cycles, which significantly increase the costs of using these materials. Metal and metal oxide NPs, graphene, CNTs, and their nanocomposites can function as adsorbents owing to their large surface area, rapid kinetics, and high affinity and reactivity towards various contaminants, which exceed the performance of conventional adsorbents (Omran and Abdel-Salam, 2021). A cost-effective novel nanoscale Moringa oleifera seed waste (nMSW) was prepared and used in a study as a novel green bio-nanosorbent for the removal of chlorpyrifos (CPF) from wastewater (Hamadeen et al., 2021). The adsorption of CPF by nMSW followed the Langmuir > Temkin > Kiselev adsorption isotherm models in that order. The maximum adsorption capacity of CPF by nMSW increased 2.75-folds (25 mg/g) over that of bulk MSW. The sorption kinetics fitted well with first-order and power function models with a maximum CPF removal efficiency of 81% within 30 min at pH 7. The thermodynamic parameters indicated that the CPF sorption reaction was spontaneous and exothermic. Hydrogen bonding, hydrophobicity, electrostatic interactions, and π–π interactions were the key forces driving the removal of CPF by nMSW.

Surfactants are frequently used to manipulate the size and shape of NMs, however environmentally friendly green capping agents are viable alternatives that have gained popularity in recent years. Agro-industrial biowaste extracts contain a variety of biomolecules such as cellulose, hemicellulose, pectin, lignin, proteins, polysaccharides, polyphenols, flavonoids, carotenoids, vitamins, dietary fibers, and essential oils, which can act as templating agents (Gómez-García et al., 2021; Omran, 2022) (Fig. 7
                        ). Agro-industrial biowaste can act as “nano-bio-factories” because the biomolecules therein contain different functional moieties that can mediate the reduction of metal salt precursors to their NP state and aid in capping and stabilizing the produced NPs (El-Gendy and Omran et al., 2019). In general, the mechanism involved in the green synthesis of NPs comprises three distinct phases, involving (i) the activation phase, during which metal ion reduction and the nucleation of the reduced atoms occur; (ii) the growth phase, wherein small adjacent NPs spontaneously coalesce to form large particles; and (iii) the final phase, in which the morphological structure of the NPs is tailored and tuned to achieve the most energetically suitable NP configuration (Shafey, 2020). When the duration of the growth phase is increased, NPs begin to aggregate and form configurations such as nanoprisms, nanotubes, nanohexahedrons, and other irregularly shaped particles (Kim et al., 2010). Controlling the growth of NPs is critical to produce uniformly shaped particles with a narrow particle size distribution. One of the general growth mechanisms that control NP synthesis is Ostwald ripening (Piwoński et al., 2016). Several biomolecules that mediate the production of green synthesized NMs for wastewater treatment are summarized in Table 2
                        .

Polyphenols are organic molecules with abundant phenolic hydroxyl groups. Polyphenol-coated NPs have attracted the attention of many researchers due to their adherent affinity and antioxidative properties. Polyphenols play a key role in the preparation, stabilization, and adjustment of multifunctional nanostructures for a wide range of applications (Papuc et al., 2017). Polyphenols are classified into three types, namely flavonoids, phenolic acids, and stilbenoids. Polyphenol-coated NPs can be formulated via covalent and non-covalent interactions and can function as effective reducing agents because of the ease with which they can donate hydrogen atoms or electrons (Akhavan et al., 2012; Guo et al., 2021) (Fig. 8
                        ). Tea polyphenols are distinguished by their hydrophilicity, biocompatibility, biodegradability, and their ability to act as effective reducing and capping agents during the synthesis of metal NPs. For instance, polyphenols can tailor the green synthesis of AgNPs and AuNPs using Ag+ and AuCl4
                        − as metal salt precursors, respectively (Heinemann et al., 2021). Additionally, the reducing potential of polyphenols has prompted their use in the synthesis of inorganic non-metallics such as graphene oxide (Xu et al., 2020), graphene (Behzadi, 2021), and CNTs (Diel et al., 2021).
